The noble town, formerly known as Celurca of celestial affinity, now rejoices as the Mount of Roses. A hill adjoins by which a river glides: both supply rich dainties to the people: salmon and whatever Nero’s ponds can yield come from the waters, choice cattle from the hill. The banks are fringed with lilies, refreshing to the eye, and the heights around glow with red roses. Eastward is the tributary sea, enlivened by countless sails. The Links form the playground of the people‚ where some youths practise horse- manship, some archery, others the “ putting '' ofthe stone with Herculean arm. Wrestling and quoits are here, and playing at ball with the crooked club. A

glimpse of thy beauties would wean Jove from his Capitol, Venus from her Idalian haunts.
